myself:-) Something like:

"The fact that rights can always be in conflict with one another
means that all human rights are contingent and none are absolute.
So, for example, if one posited a "right to encrypt" as a human
right that inherently means accepting that there are times when
that "right" would lose out in balancing of conflicting rights.
That means that there are technical concepts (e.g. arithmetic,
the ability to write code), the free exercise of which may be
better protected if they are not specifically claimed as human
rights."

(As an aside, it's interesting that you are sensitive here to
the difficultly of establishing consensus on this topic, whereas
I am not. And then we reverse roles when it comes to "Internet
architecture." Not that surprising I guess:-)

>=20
>> Specific comments (without reference to importance:-)

Will get back to these later, when I get time.

