I think you're missing my point so I'll try again.

There is a risk that IETFers take a very literal approach to
the topic of considering human rights and as a result argue
that anything they consider "good" is a human right. This
draft should, I think, help avoid that by describing at least
one major pitfall in such an approach. And I think the example
of encryption is a good one to use for this.

